## Frontend Rules (React / TypeScript)

### General
- TypeScript strict mode. No `any` types. No `// @ts-ignore`.
- All API calls go through `src/services/api.ts`. Never call `fetch` directly in a component.
- All WebSocket connections go through `src/services/ws.ts`.
- Use React Query for all server state. No `useEffect` + `fetch` patterns.

### RBAC on the frontend
Use the `useStudioAccess()` hook to determine permissions. Never hardcode role checks in components.
Unauthorised UI elements must be **absent from the DOM**, not just hidden with CSS.

```tsx
// CORRECT
const { canEdit } = useStudioAccess()
return canEdit ? <EditButton /> : null

// WRONG
return <EditButton style={{ display: canEdit ? 'block' : 'none' }} />
```

### Component structure
- One component per file. No barrel exports that re-export everything.
- Co-locate component tests: `ComponentName.tsx` + `ComponentName.test.tsx` in the same directory.
- No inline styles. Use Tailwind utility classes only.

### Streaming LLM responses
Use the `useStream()` hook for all SSE-streamed LLM responses. Never manually manage `EventSource` in a component.

---

## Testing Rules

### Backend
- `backend/tests/unit/` — pure logic, no DB, no HTTP, no real LLM. All external deps mocked.
- `backend/tests/integration/` — real test DB (rolled-back transaction per test), real FastAPI via httpx.
- `backend/tests/llm/` — real LLM API calls, tagged `@pytest.mark.llm`. Run nightly only.

Every integration test must cover:
- Happy path (correct role + valid data)
- Missing auth → 401
- Wrong role → 403
- Cross-studio violation → 403
- Invalid input → 422
- Not found → 404

### LLM test assertions — never assert string lengths
Because structured output is enforced via `chat_structured()`, tests must validate:
- Key presence (`assert isinstance(wo["title"], str) and wo["title"]`)
- Semantic relevance (keyword matching against known fixture content)
- Status/type correctness

Never assert `len(string) < N` — this is a flap risk.

### Frontend
- All component tests use MSW to intercept HTTP calls. Never mock `fetch` directly.
- Test user interactions with `@testing-library/user-event`, not `fireEvent`.
- Every component test must include a "viewer cannot perform privileged action" case.

### E2E (Playwright)
- Always use the Page Object Model (`e2e/pages/`). Never write raw `page.click()` calls in spec files.
- E2E tests use a deterministic LLM proxy — never hit the real LLM API in E2E.
- Always clean up test state in `afterEach` or use isolated test DB snapshots.

---

## Git / GitLab Rules

- Branch naming: `feat/`, `fix/`, `chore/`, `test/` prefixes
- Every commit must pass: `pytest tests/unit tests/integration` + `npm test`
- Never commit directly to `main`. Always use a merge request.
- E2E runs automatically on MR merge to `main` via GitLab CI.
- LLM regression tests run nightly. Trigger manually with `[llm-test]` in commit message.
- Coverage gate: backend line coverage must stay ≥ 90%. MR is blocked if it drops.

---

## What to never do

- Never call an LLM provider SDK directly — always go through `LLMService`
- Never generate presigned MinIO URLs for client downloads — always proxy through FastAPI
- Never use `ivfflat` for pgvector indexes — always use `hnsw`
- Never save only plain text to `sections.content` on a Yjs debounce — always dual-write with `yjs_state`
- Never skip the RBAC dependency chain — never check roles manually in route handlers
- Never return a raw SQLAlchemy model from an API endpoint — always use a Pydantic schema
- Never write implementation code without a failing test first
- Never delete a test to make a build pass
- Never modify an existing Alembic migration — always create a new one
- Never use `any` in TypeScript
- Never call `fetch` directly in a React component — always use `src/services/api.ts`
- Never hide unauthorised UI elements with CSS — remove them from the DOM entirely
